# Core Architecture & Boundaries

- **App Router separation**
  - Use `app/` only for routing, layouts, and page-level composition.
  - Keep side-effects and external API calls out of React components; delegate to `app/api/**` routes or `lib/**` utilities.

- **Backend-in-frontend pattern**
  - Treat `app/api/**` as the backend entry layer; never call X API or OpenAI directly from client components.
  - API routes should delegate provider-specific logic to a service layer and integration layer instead of inlining HTTP calls.

- **Layering rules (target structure)**
  - `integrations/**` will own external provider integrations (X API, OpenAI, future platforms) and low-level SDK calls.
  - `services/**` will own app-level orchestration and business logic, calling into `integrations/**` and shared helpers.
  - `lib/**` is reserved for small, framework-agnostic utilities and helpers that can be safely shared across layers.
  - `components/**` and `hooks/**` are UI/client-only and must not import from `app/api/**`, `services/**`, or `integrations/**`, or read process env vars.
  - `app/api/**` may import from `services/**`, `lib/**`, `types/**`, and `utils/**` but must not import UI components.

- **Token & secret handling**
  - Access tokens, refresh tokens, and OpenAI keys must only be used on the server (API routes or `lib/**` used by API routes).
  - Do not expose raw tokens to the client; client components should work with opaque IDs or safe, derived data only.
